column168: Description Of Events

EVIDENCE OF A SPILL WAS NOTICED DURING THE DAILY FACILITY INSPECTION.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS PROBABLY FROM A LEAKING DRUM OF CLEAN MINERAL SPIRITS FROM THE BACK OF A TRUCK THAT WAS PARKED AT THAT SPOT. ACTION WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND TO COVER AREA WITH ABSORBANTS.  A SPILL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR WAS THEN CONTACTED TO USE A FIELD DETECTOR TO IDENTIFY AND REMOVE ANY FURTHER CONTAMINATED SOIL AND ASPHALT.  THOROUGH DRUM INSPECTIONS AND TIMING TRUCKS WITH BOOMS TO BE DONE.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: V11 OR V111 ABOVE NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED. OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO DELIVER A BULK LOAD OF #4 OIL TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AT THE HOSPITAL. AFTER DRIVER HAD BEEN UNLOADING FOR A FEW MINUTES, THE OIL STARTED TO BLOW BACK UP OUT OF THE FILL PIPE. HE STOPPED UNLOADING AND CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE VENT PIPE FOR THE UNDERGROUND TANK WAS OBSTRUCTED  CAUSING THE TANK TO PRESSURIZE. THE PRESSURE CAUSED THE OIL TO COME BACK OUT THE FILL PIPE AND ONTO THE SIDEWALK AND LAWN. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY WAS CALLED IN AND REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED DEBRIS. THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR REPRESENTATIVE OVERSAW THE CLEANUP. THE REFERENCE NUMBER ASSIGNED BY THEM IS 9310571. THE HOSPITAL HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION WITH THE VENTING SYSTEM TO AVOID FUTURE PROBLEMS.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRANSFERING MATERIAL FROM ONE DRUM TO ANOTHER AND THE DRUM HE WAS LIFTING SLIPPED OUT OF HIS HANDS.  THE DRUM CONTAINED 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL AND WAS RECOVERED WITH ABSORBANT SOCKS AND ABSORBANT SHEETS.  THE SPILL OCCURED ON CONCRETE ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND NOTHING WAS LOST TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED THAT DRUM TO DRUM TRANSFERS MUST BE DONE WITH A PUMP.

THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.  A COPY OF THIS REPORT IS BEING SENT TO THE ORIGIN CUSTOMER SERVICE ACCOUNT EXECUTIVE FOR FOLLOW UP.

column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING THROUGH CORRUGATED CARTON, WAS OPENED AND INSPECTED.  CAPS WERE FOUND OPENED ON FOUR OF THE TWELVE BOTTLES.  SHIPPER WAS CALLED IN DENVER, CO.  AND WE WERE REFERRED TO THE MAIN OFFICE IN LIVONIA, MICHIGAN.  TALKED TO KATHRYN WALLACE AND SHE REQUESTED WE SEND THE PACKAGE TO HER.  WE REPACKED IN DOUBLE PLASTIC BAGS, AFTER WE SECURED THE LIDS AND WE PLACED SOME ABSORBANT MATERIAL WITH BOTTLES AND SENT BACK MICHIGAN.  SECURE CAPS AND TAMPER PROOF SEAL COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE LEAKAGE.

THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN THE PRIMARY UNLOAD LEAKING.  THE PACKGAE WAS TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA WHERE IT WAS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.  PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT USED INCLUDED GOGGLES, GLOVES, APRON AND BOOTS ALL PPE WAS DECONTAMINATED FOLLOWING CLEANUP.

A PACKAGE CONTAINING DIESEL FUEL (FLAMMABLE LIQUID) WAS FOUND IN THE UNLOAD AND WAS SPILLED DUE TO A LOOSE FITTING VALVE.  THE DAMAGE CONTENTS WERE REWRAPPED AND RETURN TO SHIPPER.  WASTE WAS DISPOSED ACCORDING TO LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATION.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  CONTENTS THAT LEAKED OUT WAS NEUTRALIZED, ABSORBED, AND PLACED IN A SPILL TRAY AS WAS THE LEAKY PACKAGE.  UPON INSPECTION ONE OF FOUR GALLONS OF METHANE SULFONIC ACID SOLUTION HAD A BOTTOM END CRACKED SEAM.  THE ENTIRE GALLON ALONG WITH CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD AND MERICULITE WERE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

AS HE BEGAN TO LOWER THE LIFTGATE ON THE TRUCK 1 DRUM WHICH WAS NOT BALANCED PROPERLY FELL OVER CAUSING WASTE PAINT RELATED, MATERIALS TO ESCAPE.  THE DRIVER QUICKLY ASSESED THE SITUATION AND UPRIGHTED THE DRUM, AND CONTAINED THE SPILL. THE SPILL WAS THEN CLEANED UP USING ABSORBANT PADS AND OIL DRY.  ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND DISPOSED OF USING ALL PROPER METHODS.  THE SAME EVENT CAN BE PREVENTED IN THE FUTURE IF THE DRIVER MAKES SURE THAT ALL DRUMS ARE CHECKED FOR STEADINESS AND BALANCE.

column168: WASTE HYDROCHLORIC ACID (HAZARDOUS WASTE NO K069) WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM THE WHEELING-PITTSBURGH STEEL CORP., ALLENPORT PLANT TO THE MILL SERVICE INC., (msi) YUKON PLANT ON DECEMBER 1, 1993. WHILE CLIMBING A HILL ENROUTE TO THE YUKON PLANT, WASTE ACID OVERFOLOWED THE CONTAINMENT SUMP CONSTRUCTED AROUND THE CARGO TANK LOADING HATCH AND WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE. THE DRIVER APPARENTLY FAILED TO NOTICE, DURING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND WHILE LOADING THE VEHICLE THROUGH THE HATCH THAT THE HATCH WAS NOT SECURELY FASTENED TO THE CARGO TANK. THE HATCH HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE CARGO TANK PRIOR TO THIS SHIPMENT TO FACILITATE A REPAIR TO THE UNIT AND HAD NOT BEEN SECURELY REFASTENED. WASTE ACID APPARENTLY LEAKED FROM THE LOOSE FITTING DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, FILLING THE CONTAINMENT DEVICE AND RESULTING IN THE SPILL WHEN THE TRUCK ASCENDED THE STEEP GRADE. MSI DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE OF THE SPILL, WHICH WAS 1000 FEET OF THE YUKON PLANT ENTRANCE. THE SPILLED WASTE WAS ABSORBED AND THE ROAD SURFACE CLEANED. THE SPILL DID NOT LEAVE THE ROAD SURFACE. THE ORIGINAL LADING AND THE SPILL RESIDUES WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE YUKON PLANT UNDER THE AUTHORITY OF THE US ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY AND THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES. NO HEALTH RISKS WERE ASSOCIATED WITH THE SPILL AND NO EVACUATION WAS REQUIRED. FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE WILL BE PREVENTED BY REMINDING DRIVERS OF THE NEED FOR THOROUGH PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS. WE ARE ALSO INVESTIGATING THE NEED FOR ADDITIONAL MEASURES TO ENSURE THAT VEHICLES SUBJECT TO MAINTENANCE ARE INSPECTED PRIOR TO BEING RETURNED TO SERVICE.

column168: A POLY LINED 17H 55 CONTAINING NITRIC ACID /SULFURIC ACID WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON STEEL DRUM. THE DRUM WAS DROPPED INTO THE OVERPACK WHICH CAUSED THE LINER TO RIP. THE ACID REACTED WITH THE STEEL INNER DRUM AND LIBERATED GAS. INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS GREAT ENOUGH TO BLOW THE LID OFF THE OVERPACK. THE LID HIT THE TRAILER ROOF AND TORE A 1 FT HOLE. THE FORCE PUSHED THE INTERNAL DRUM OUT OF THE OVERPACK. THE INTERNAL DRUM BOTTOM WAS ALSO BLOWN OFF CAUSING THE CONTENTS APPROX 50 GALLONS TO SPILL ON TRAILER AND 20-30 GALLONS OF THIS LEAKED ON THE GROUND. DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER AND GROUND WAS HANDLED BY THE CLIENT (DIVERSEY CORP). LIME WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID. WATER AND OILSORB WAS USED TO RINSE AND CLEAN THE TRAILER AND GROUND. THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT WAS DRUMMED UP AND WILL BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. RYDER WAS DISPATCHED TO REPAIR THE HOLE IN THE ROOF. THE TRAILER WAS OFF LOADED AND THE DRUMS WERE WIPED DOWN TO REMOVE ANY CONTAMINATION.  THE TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO SIT ALL NIGHT WITH A FAN TO DRY FLOOR. DRUMS WERE RELOADED AND SECURED. THE DRUMS THAT ARE ON LINE ITEM 11 (A) OF THE MANIFEST WERE NOT RELOADED, THEY ARE BEING INSPECTED TO SEE IF THEY WILL NEED TO BE REPACKAGED BEFORE TRANSPORATION AT A LATER DATE.

column168: MATLACK INC. PICKED UP 20' TANK ON FLAT BED; DELIVERED TO SEA-LAND SERVICE FOR EXPORT.  UPON ARRIVAL WAS INSPECTED AND PRODUCT WAS FLOWING OUT OF OVERFLOW VENTS.  PAT PARRISH, SEA-LAND'S SAFETY SUPERVISOR, NOTIFIED PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT TO SECURE AREA. THEIR RESPONSE TEAM INVESTIGATED; THE DOGS INTACT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THERE WAS A LOOSE VALVE. TEXAS WATER COMMISSION AND THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY CENTER WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  WHEN THE TANK WAS IN THE INSPECTION LANE, APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED ABSORBANT OVER PRODUCT AND ROPED OFF AREA.  HOYER, THE SHIPPER, WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SUPPLIER, ROHM AND HAAS, HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO REPAIR THE TANK.  ROHM AND HAAS TEAM PLACED THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBANT INTO A DRUM TO BE PICKED UP ON 12/21 BY A TRANSPORTER CARRIER APPROVED TO TRANSPORT HAZARDOUS WASTE.  AFTER THE TANK WAS REPAIRED, THE SHIPPER HAD THE TANK SENT TO THE SUPPLIER TO BE PRESSURE TESTED.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS SHIPPED FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4875 SPRING GROVE AVE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED ON THE BOTTOM CHIME OF 2 OF THE CONTAINERS RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED THE 2 CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILTIY.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR AND TRAILER CAME STRAIGHT INTO THE TERMINAL AND WAS WASHED OUT WITH WATER TO REMOVE THE CORROSIVE LIQUID PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM DAVE COLLINS, AAA COOPER SAFETY DIRECTOR.  55 GALLON DRUM WAS ALSO WASHED OUT WITH WATER BEFORE DISPOSAL.

UNLOADER SWITCHED TO SECOND TANK WHILE FILLING SECOND TANK.  UNLOADER CAME OUT AND TOLD DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN.  FIRST TANK WAS LEAKING.  DRIVER WENT INSIDE AND CHECKED TANK AND IT WAS LEAKING AT THE 300 GALS MARK AT THE SEAM.  CONSIGNEE HOOKED UP PUMP AND STARTED TO UNLOAD FIRST TANK.  BOTH TANKS WERE IN DIKE AREA.  CONSIGNEE WAS NEUTRALIZING MATERIAL IN DIKE AREA AND TOLD DRIVER THEY WOULD PUMP IT OUT. AFTER PUMPING 400 GALS. OUT OF SECOND TANK THEY TOLD DRIVER TO UNLOAD BALANCE OF PRODUCT.

THE WASH RACK ATTENDANT DID NOT PERFORM THE PRESSURE TEST PORTION OF THE TEST WHICH WOULD HAVE IDENTIFIED THE OPEN VALVE AND WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL. THE OLIN OPERATORS SHOULD HAVE REJECTED THE TRAILER BECAUSE IT DID NOT HAVE AN AIR PAD ON IT WHEN IT ARRIVED FOR LOADING.  EACH OF US HAD AN OPPORTUNITY TO PREVENT THE SPILL.  THE DSI PERSON HAD BEEN GIVEN A TWO WEEK SUSPENSION FOR FAILING TO PERFORM HIS DUTIES AS DIRECTED.

A METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED WITH SEEPAGE FROM A FAULTY LID, WHEN UNLOADING A TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, THE LID WAS FOUND TO NOT BE SUITABLE FOR REPAIR.  THE PAIL WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW D.O.T. APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELA APPLIED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED THE PAIL RETURNED TO THEM FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, A STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A PUNCTURE.  THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW D.O.T. APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED. THE SPILLAGE WAS ALSO PROPERLY RECOOPERED.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIMS CREDIT.

THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE HAD GONE TO WORK AT ABOUT MIDNIGHT ON DECEMBER 11, 1993.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 A.M.  THE DRIVER APPARENTLY FELL ASLEEP.  THE VEHICLE WAS WESTBOUND IN THE RIGHT LANE OF INTERSTATE 80, HAULING A TANKER LOADED WITH 6,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. THE ROAD CURVES VERY SLIGHTLY TO THE LEFT AT THIS POINT,  THE TRUCK WENT STRAIGHT OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD FOR APPROXI,MATELY 90 FEET BEFORE IT ENCOUNTERED A GUARDRAIL BEFORE A BRIDGE.  IT TOOK OUT 175 FEET OF GUARDRAIL, CLIPPED AN EDGE OF THE BRIDGE RAILING AND WENT AIRBOURNE OVER A GRAVEL COUNTY ROAD THAT RUNS UNDERNEATH THE INTERSTAE.  THE TRUCK IMPACTED ON THE CONCRETE WING UNDERNEATH THE BRIDGE, ON THE WEST SIDE, AND THEN SLID UP THE WING UNTIL THE CAB WAS LYING ON THE DIRT SHOULDER NEXT TO THE WESTBOUND LANE OF THE INTERSTATE, JUST WEST OF THE END OF THE BRIDGE.  THE DRIVER WAS EJECTED AND WAS FOUND LYING ON HIS BACK ON THE DIRT SHOULDER BETWEEN THE CAB AND THE INTERSTATE HIGHWAY.  THE TRACTOR BROKE UP ON IMPACT.  THE ENGINE, TRANSMISSION AND FRONT AXLE WERE THROWN FREE OF THE REST OF THE WRECKAGE.  THE AXLE WAS LOCATED WEST OF THE REST OF THE TRUCK BY APPROXIMATELY 20 OR 30 FEET.  THE ENGINE AND TRANSMISSION WERE IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE FRAME.  THE FRONT BUMPER FROM THE TRUCK LANDED ON THE RIGHT LANE WESTBOUND ON THE INTERSTAE JUST PAST THE BRIDGE.

DRUM WAS UNLOADED OFF TRAILER P5209.  NO LEAKAGE WAS SHOWN ON TRAILER. LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED ON SAVANNAH DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART LEAKED OUT FROM AROUND SEAM WHICH SEEMS TO BE DEFECTIVE.  DRUMS WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND PLACED ON A PALLET WHICH STOPPED LEAKAGE.  THE QUART THAT LEAKED EVAPORATED.  DRUM IS NOW IN A WELL VENTILATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AREA. HAVE AUTHORIZATION FROM SHIPPER FOR RETURN.  WILL BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER IN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RECOVERY DRUM.

WHEN TRAILER WAS UNLOADED, IT WAS NOTICED THAT ONE BOX WAS LEAKING.  PAIL WAS CRACKED ON BOTTOM, DEFECTIVE PAIL WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM WITH BOX AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  IT IS UNKNOWN WHETHER MATERIAL WAS LOADED IN THIS CONDITION BY SHIPPER OR WHETHER THE DEFECTIVE PAIL CRACKED IN TRANSIT.  SPILLS OF THIS NATURE MAY BE PREVENTED BY USING ONLY PACKAGING MATERIALS THAT WILL WITHSTAND THE TRAUMA OF SHIPMENT.

BOTH MATERIALS WERE PACKAGES IN FIBERBOARD (CARDBOARD) BOXES WITH CARDBOARD DIVIDERS, DOT 12.  EACH BOX CONTAINED ONLY ONE, ONE GALLON GLASS BOTTLES WITH OPEN SPACE FOR THREE MORE.  DURING TRANSPORT, UNAUTHORIZE DOT BOX FELL APART ALLOWING EACH BOTTLE TO BREAK, CAUSING MINOR SPILL OF MATERIAL.  HM-181 PACKAGING AUTHORIZATION CALLS FOR DOT 4 G FIBERBOARD BOX.  SPOKE WITH SHIPPER WHO ADVISED HE DID NOT KNOW ABOUT THE NEW PACKAGING AUTHORIZE.

column168: THE STORE HAD ORDERED TOO MUCH UNLEADED. column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST ON WEST VIRGINIA STATE RT #38 APPROACHING JUNCTION OF STATE RT #92.  DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF UNIT, ATTEMPTED TO NEGOCIATE A SHARPE CURVE TO THE LEFT, WENT INTO CURVE TOO FAST, TANK ROLLED TO RIGHT SIDE AND BROKE LOOSE FROM THE TRACTOR COMING TO REST 2/3'S OVER IN THE DITCH AND AGAINST THE HILLSIDE. TANK WAS DAMAGED AND PRODUCT RELEASED.  AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  FIRE DEPARTMENTS THAT WERE ON SCENE ARE AS FOLLOWS: PHILLIPI, BELINGTON, JUNIOR, ELKINS, NUTTERFORK, BRIDGEPORT, ANMORE, STONEWOOD, GRAFTON, BUCHANNON, WARREN DISTRICT, FELLOWSVILLE AND COALTON.  OTHER AGENCIES REPRESENTED AT THE INCIDENT WERE WEST VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER HAD BEEN NOTIFIED BY THE OFFICER ON SCENE EARLIER.  WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL AND SPILL AREA.

column168: UTLX 38648 NOTED EMITTING VAPORS IN CARRIER RAILYARD.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  CONSIGNEE WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO SCENE.  TO TIGHTEN LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT ON GAUGING DEVICE.  CAR SAFE FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

ACFX 84990 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING LIQUID AT MANWAY DURING CAR SWITCHING.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  CAR WAS GOING TO FLEET TRANSPORT IN LOUISVILLE, KY.  THEY ARRANGED FOR PESCO LTD. TO REPAIR.  A REPRESENTATIVE OF PESCO, RAY WILLHITE, REPLACED GASKET AND OK'ED CAR FOR MOVEMENT AT 10:55 AM.

SUNX 60245 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE EMITTING VAPORS FROM DOME OF CAR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER FOUND A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND REPLACED.  CAR WAS THEN SAFE TO MOVE.

GATX 19047 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM DOME AREA.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER SENT A REPRESENTATIVE WHO REPLACED A DOME GASKET.  TANK WAS REPAIRED 1/4/94 AND ALLOWED TO MOVE TO DESTINATION.

BLACK WAS CALLED TO PERFORM DECONTAMINATION, CLEANUP AND INSPECTION DUTIES. THE DAMAGED ITEMS WERE RECOUPED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. column168: TANK CAR CAME INTO CSXT'S RAILYARD IN NASHVILLE, TN AND WAS OBSERVED TO SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN IT MOVED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR THE CONSIGNNEE TO RESPOND AND REPAIR THE EAR. THE CONSIGNEE'S PEOPLE INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A SECUREMENT BOLT AND NUT ON THE 8" FILL HOLE COVER WAS STRIPPED AND WOULD NOT TIGHTEN DOWN TO SECURE THE COVER. THE SHIPPER CALLED FOR AN AFC MOBILE UNIT TO RESPOND. LENIT RESPONDED ON 12/7/93, REPAIRED THE FILL HOLE COVER, AND SECURED THE CAR. CAR WAS RELEASED ON 12/8/93.

AT CSXT RAILYARD IN GRAND RAPIDS, MI, YARD JOB Y10306 WAS PULLING CANS OUT OF E06 TRACK AND DERAILED 4 RAIL CARS INCLUDING A TANK CAR OF MAETHANOL. THE METHANOL CAR WAS LEANING AND LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM AND TOP OPERATING ROD PACKING GLAND NUT WHICH WAS LOOSE. CSXT CALLED YOUNGS ENV., AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND. TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND NUT AND STOPPED THE LEAK. WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PROCDUCT WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSLOADED BEFORE REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. CONTENTS OF GATX 52932 WAS TRANSFERRED TO CTX 23461 IN 12/22/93.

CSXT TRAIN, Q595-08 STOPPED BY MAINTENANCE OF WAY FORCES AT ATHERTON, IN ON ACCOUNT OF STRONG ODORS COMING FROM TRAIN AS IT PASSED BY. TRAIN CREW INSPECTED TRAIN AND FOUND TANK CAR WITH STAIN ON SIDE AND ODOR BUT NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE. TRAIN WAS PULLED FORWARD A COUPLE OF CAR LENGTH AND STOPPED TO SHAKE CAR. MECHANICAL PERSON ON SCENE, SAW PRDUCT SLOSH OUT OF TOP OF CAR. CAR WAS SET OUT ON LEAD IN CFI INDUSTRIES AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA, RESPONDED AND FOUND CAR HAD A BAD MANWAY GASKET. SPILL RECOVERY REPLACED THE GASKET. RESECURED THE MANWAY AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SHIPPER LOCATION TO LAOD. HE FAILED TO CONFIRM THAT THE VALVES ON HIS CARGO TANK WERE PROPERLY SECURED WHEN THE SHIPPER STARTED TO LOAD THE CARGO TANK PRODUCT ESCAPED. OUR DRIVER SHUT THE VALVES TO STOP HTE LOSS AND THE LOADING WAS COMPLETED. THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE SHIPPER.

column168: THESE DRUMS WERE SHIPPED INTO SAFETY KLEEN CORP NORCROSS ON 12-29-93 FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE. WHILE THERE ON 12-31-93 IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT FROM A LOWER SIDE BUNGS OF 1 DRUM AND 2 OTHER DRUMS SIDE BUNGS WERE STARTING TO LEAK. THE BUNGS STILL HAD THE ORIGINAL SEALEDS. POSSIBLE THE LEAK COULD HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY DEFECTIVE BUNGS AND GASKETS OR CORROSIVE OR MAYBE COLD WEATHER BY FREEZING. THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED OUT LOOK LIKE WATER. MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS ALONG WITH LEAKING DRUMS. TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS CHECK SIDE BUNGS MORE CLOSELY.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEVELAND PNEUMATIC COMPANY LOCATED AT 2800 E 33RD ST IN CLEVELAND, OH TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVE IN CINCINNATI OH. UPON ARIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY .5 GALLONS OF 1,1,1,-TRICHLOROETHYLENE HAD LEAKED FROM THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. UPON EXAMINATION OF THE CONTAINER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A TIGHT SEAL WAS NOT ACHIEVED BETWEEN THE GASKET AND THE LID OF THE CONTAINER. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKLED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBED THE RELEASED MATERIAL WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND WAS FOUND TO BE IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION. DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

A VAN TRAILER CONTIANING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM LANCASTER SYNTHESIS, INC. LOCATED AT 257 HIRAM RD IN BLYTHEWOOD, SC TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVE. DURING UNLOADING PROCEDURES, THE FORK-LIFT OEPRATOR USED BARREL GRABBERS TO MOVE THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION. THE EXTERNAL PRESSURE PLACED ON THE CONTAINER TO DISLODGE CAUSING THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED THE FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPLACED THE CONTAINER LID. ALL SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, ALL PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO USE PALLETS WHEN MOVING CONTAINERS NOT SUITABLE TO BE MOVED USING THE BARREL GRABBER ATTACHMENT OF HTE FORK-LIFT.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM MS CHAMBER & SONS LOCATED AT 1104 W ROSELYN RD IN COLONIAL HEIGHTS, VA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK RD IN BRISTOL, CT. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD RUPTURED DUE TO SUBFREEZING TEMPERATURES THAT CAUSED THE CONTENTS WITHIN THE CONTAINER TO EXPAND. APPROXIMATELY 40 LBS OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY RECONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL AND DECONTAMINATED THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE. ALL MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND WAS FOUND TO BE IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION. DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

A CARGO TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WAS WAS ENROUTE FROM GE PLASTICS LOCATED AT 1 LEXAN LN IN MT. VERNON, IN TO ESSROC MATERIALS, INC. LOCATED AT STATE ROAD 25 SOUTH IN LOGANSPORT, IN. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATON FACILITY, THE DRIVER POSITIONED THE VEHICLE AT THE UNLOADING AREA WHERE ESSROC FACILITY PERSONNEL INITIATED THE UNLOADING PROCEDURES. DURING THE COURSE OF THE OFF-LOADING PROCEDURES, BOTH THE EXTERNAL AND INTERNAL VALVES OF THE TRAILER WERE OPENED BY ESSROC PERSONNEL BUT THE DELIVERY HOSE HAD NOT YET BEEN ATTACHED. AT THIS POINT, PRODUCT BEGAN TO FLOW THROUGH THE VALVES ONTO THE CONTAINMENT PAD OF THE OFF-LOADING AREA. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE EMERGENCY VALVE ON THE TRAILER AND INITIATED CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES. ALL MATERIAL RELEASED TO THE CONTAINMENT PAD WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. THE TANK TRAILER AND CONTAINMENT PAD WERE DECONTAMINATED AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS SAFELY OFF-LOADED FROM THE VEHICLE. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL VALVES WERE INSPECTED AND WERE FOUND TO BE OPERATIONAL AND IN THE CLOSED POSITION. ALL DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO CONDUCT PROPER PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS TO INSURE ALL EQUIPMENT IS OPERATIONAL AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION IN THE EVENT A DEFICIENCY IS IDENTIFIED.

A CARGO TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS SHIPPED FROM LUCAS SUMITOMO BRAKES, INC. LOCATED AT 1650 KINGS DR IN LEBANON, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND MOVED TO THE VEHICLE STAGING AREA PENDING DISPATCH. AT THIS POINT, A SECOND DRIVER PREPARED TO TAKE THIS VEHICLE OUT AND DURING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION DISCOVERED THAT THE CONTAINMENT TRAYS FOR THE DELIVERY HOSES CONTAINED RESIDUAL PRODUCT THAT HAD NOT BEEN DRAINED FROM THE HOSED BY THE PREVIOUS DRIVER. THE DRIVER MOVED THE VEHICLE ONTO THE CONTAINMENT PAD, OPENED THE TRAY DRAINS AND FLUSHED THE HOSE TRAYS. ON FINISHED, THE DRIVER NEGLECTED TO CLOSE THE TRAY DRAINS AND PROCEEDED TO DRIVE OFF THE TRUCK PADC ALLOWING RINSE WATER REMAINING IN THE HOSE TRAYS TO ESCAPED FROM THE CONTAINMENT TRAYS ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. FACILITY PERSONNEL THEN INITIATED CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES AND ABSORBED THE FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION,THE DRIVERS INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL HOSES ARE DRAINED AND CAPPED BEFORE PLACING THEM IN THE HOSE TRAYS AND THAT A THOROUGH PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OCCURS PRIOR TO MOVING ANY VEHICLE TO IDENTIFY AND DEFECT OR DEFICIENCY.

THE DRIVER OF THE TRANSWEST TANK LINES WAS UNLOADING JET A FUEL FROM THE CARGO TANK TRAILER INTO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. THERE WAS DIFFICULTY GETTING THE FUEL TO FLOW. A JET MECHANIC WITH  WESTCOR AVIATION ACTIVATED A PUMP AT THE FUEL ISLAND IN AN ATTEMPT TO ASSIST THE DRIVER. THE PUMP BEGAN TRANSFERRING THE FUEL FROM THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK BACK INTO THE CARGO TANK TRAILER. WHEN THE COMPARTMENT FILLED UP IT CAUSED THE FUEL TO PRESSURE BACK THROUGH THE VAPOR RECOVERY TUBE AND ONTO THE CEMENT PAD AROUND THE FUEL ISLAND. THE PUMP WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN.  THE SCOTTSDALE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND COVERED THE SPILL AREA WITH WATER BASED FOAM.  THE FUEL EVAPORATED AND A SECOND COAT OF FOAM WAS APPLIED. SPILL PREVENTION TRAINING WAS GIVEN TO THE DRIVER IN A POST INCIDENT INTERVIEW.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 HOURS ON 12-22-93, ONE OF OUR TRANSPORT DRIVERS WAS PREPARING TO TRANSFER 9000 GALLONS OF LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS (LP-GAS) FROM OUR TRANSPORT UNIT #516 TO BULK STORAGE PLANT #0911 LOCATED AT BOWDON, GA.  OUR DRIVER HAD FINISHED HOOKING UP THE LIQUID HOSE AND WAS PREPARING TO HOOK UP THE VAPOR HOSE WHEN A DISCHARGE OF LP-GAS FROM THE VAPOR OUTLET IGNITED, RESULTING IN SEVERE BURNS TO OUR DRIVER, DAVID BOWMAN.            DAVID, PRESUMABLY IN A STATE OF SHOCK, VACATED THE AREA AND WAS ABOUT 300 YARDS WEST OF THE BULK PLANT WHEN EMERGENCY REPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.          FIREFIGHTERS SHUT OFF THE VAPOR DISCHARGE, AND MOVED THE TRANSPORT UNIT AWAY FROM THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE FIRE.  NO DAMAGE OCCURRED TO THE TRANSPORT UNIT AS THE FIRE SOURCE WAS THE VAPOR OUTLET ON THE UNIT.            WHEN OPENING THE INTERNAL VAPOR VALVE, I BELIEVE DAVIDS HAND HIT THE BALL SHUTOFF VALVE, WHICH LOCATED JUST BEFORE THE VAPOR OUTLET AND ADJACENT TO THE CONTROL LEVERS, OPENING BOTH THE INTERNAL VALVE AND THE BALL VALVE SIMULTANEOUSLY. THIS WOULD ALLOW A SUBSTANTIAL AMOUNT OF VAPOR TO BE DISCHARGED TO THE ATMOSPHERE. DUE TO THE DESIGN OF THE PIPING SYSTEM ON THE TRANSPORT, THERE CONCEIVABLY COULD HAVE BEEN ENOUGH LIQUID IN THE VAPOR LINE, THAT WHEN RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE COULD CREATE A STATIC DISCHARGE CAPABLE OF IGNITING THE VAPOR.  THIS LIQUID WOULD HAVE COME FROM SLOSHING AND SPRAY FILLING.                 AS A CORRECTIVE MEASURE TO PREVENT AN INCIDENT OF THIS TYPE FROM RECURRING, ALL TRANSPORT DRIVERS IN THE COMPANY WILL BE INSTRUCTED NOT TO OPEN ANY VALVES UNTIL ALL HOSES ARE CONNECTED, MAINTAINING A CLOSED SYSTEM WHICH WILL VIRTUALLY ELIMINATE THE POSSIBILITY OF IGNITION BY STATIC ELECTRICITY.

column168: A CARGO TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ROHM AND HASS DELEWARE VALLEY, INC. LEMONT PLANT LOCATED AT MAIN ST AND MALEY RD IN LEMONT IL, TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, FACILITY PERSONNEL OPENED THE TOP DOME HATCH TO SAMPLE THE MATERIAL. THE DRIVER WAS THEN INSTRUCTED TO MOVE THE VEHICLE TO THE UNLOADING AREA, PRIOR TO MOVING THE VEHICLE, THE DRIVER VISUALLY INSPECTED THE DOME HATCH BUT DID NOT PHYSICALLY CHECK TO MAKE SURE ALL THE BOLTS OF THE HATCH WERE SECURED. WHEN THE DRIVER MOVED THE VEHICLE, THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK SURGED TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE DOME HATCH. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATEY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED THE SPILLED MATERIAL WITH SPEEDI DRY. IN ADDITION, THE OUTSIDE OF THE CARGO TANK WAS DECONTAMINATED AND THE DOME HATCH SECURED PRIOR TO PROCEEDING TO THE OFF-LOADING AREA. ALL SUPPLIES USED IN THE CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATION OPERATIONS WERE DISPOSED OF THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THE LOADING, UNLOADING, SAMPLING & MOVING OF CARGO TANKS HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER PRE-TRIP PROCEDURES AND INSPECTIONS THAT MUST BE TAKEN PRIOR TO MOVING ANY VEHICLE.

IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE GASKETS OF TWO OF THE CONTAINERS WAS MISSING RESULTING IN THE RELEASE. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND RECONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINERS AND CLOSED THE CONTAINERS USING THE REQUIRED GASKETS. THE MATERIAL WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LAODED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

THIS CONTAINER ARRIVED AT THE RAIL INTERMODEL FACILITY WITH A GUN SHOT HOLE IN THE LEFT SIDE, APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET UP, AND 5 FEET REAR OF FRONT. THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER WAS REMOVED AND WORKED AT SHIPPER FACILITY.  THIS UNIT HAD NOT ENTERED RAIL TRANSPORATION SYSTEM.

A PLASTIC BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CATCH THE DRIPS.  CELANESE TEAM TIGHTENED PACKING GLAND NUT ON GAGING DEVICE AND STOPPED LEAK.  LIME WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT ON CAR SIDES AND GROUND.  PRODUCT IN BUCKET WAS TAKEN FOR DISPOSAL BY SHIPPERS TEAM.

OUR EMPLOYEE HAD HOOKED UP ALL HIS HOSES TO THE PUMP ON HIS TRAILER AND BEGAN TO PUMP OFF HIS LOAD.  THE DRIVER UNKNOWINGLY HOOKED THE PUMP UP BACKWARD.  HE PUMPED PRODUCT OUT OF THE CUSTOMER'S TANK INTO HIS TANK AND OVERFILLED HIS TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 25-30 GALLONS RAN ONTO THE GROUND BEFORE HE COULD SHUT THE PUMP OFF.  CUSTOMER PUT ABSORBANT PADS ON THE PRODUCT AND CLEANED UP.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTAION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT TANK CAR ACFX 88488 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. ALL EIGHT OF THE COVER PLATE TIE BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. THE GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. ALL EIGHT OF THE COVER PLATE TIE DOWN BOLTS WERE THEN PROPERLY SECURED. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATION WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: V11 & V111 ABOVE: NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED. OUR DRIVER WAS TRANSFERING DIESEL FUEL FROM OUR CARGO TANK TO A TEMPORARY ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT A CONSTRUCTION SITE. THE EMPLOYEE OF THE CONSTRUCTION COMPANY SET THE VALVES ON THEIR TANK AND INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO START THE TRANSFER. THE CONSTRUCTION CO. EMPLOYEE DID NOT TELL OUR DRIVER THAT THE TANK HE WAS FILLING WAS DIVIDED INTO TWO COMPARTMENTS OF DIFFERENT SIZES. FILLING BOTH COMPARTMENTS AT ONCE CAUSED THE SMALLER COMPARTMENT TO FILL FIRST AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF DIESEL FUEL CAME OUT THE TOP DOME COVER AND SPILLED INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA SURROUNDING THE TEMPORARY STORAGE TANK. SPILL CLEANED UP BY REMOVING LIQUID AND WIPING DOWN LINER IN CONTAINMENT AREA. THE N.Y.S. DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED. THEIR REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 9310797.

ON 11/29/93 AT APPROX. 6PM REEDER RECEIVED A CALL OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT SETTEGAST YARD.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER OBSERVED A STREAM OF LIQUID RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS A SMALL HOUSING ON TOP OF THE CAR.  REEDER REMOVED TEXAS EASTMAN SEAL 168660 TO OPEN THE COVER.  INSIDE, REEDER FOUND THE LEAK COMING FROM THE PLUG IN THE GAUGING DEVICE.  THE PLUG HAS A HOLE APPROX. 1MM IN DIAMETER DRILLED IN IT.  THE VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED.  REEDER CLOSED THE VALVE AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE POINTER AND SAFETY BRACKET ASSEMBLY THAT COVER THE GAUGING ROD WERE ALSO TURNED OUT OF PLACE.  THESE WERE RETURNED TO THEIR PROPER LOCATION.  THE HOUSING WAS RESEALED WITH MP 17 169099.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AND MOVED WITHOUT DELAY.

column168: AT 1030 HOURS DECEMBER 1, 1993 TRAIN LNF83-30 DERAILED WHILE HEADING INTO TRACK 204, CO BLUFFS, YARD CAR NATX 29299 HAD ONE SET OF WHEELS OFF AND UPON INSPECTING DIRECTOR L.R. TIERNEY NOTED A SLIGHT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE.  REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE ON ARRIVAL TIGHTENED THE FOUR CAP SCREWS ON THE FLANGE AND SLOWED THE LEAK TO 4 DROPS PER MINUTE.  CONTACTED MR PAGAL AT MINNESOTA CORN PROCESSING AND WAS ADVISED THAT CAR UTLX 201333 WOULD BE SENT FOR THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT.  CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A "ACF LOW PROFILE, BOTTOM OPERATED VALVE".  THE LEAKAGE WAS AT THE FLANGE WHERE VALVE ATTACHES TO CAR BY FOUR 9/16 CAP SCREWS.  THE THREE INCH VALVE ON THE LIQUID LINE HAD THE PLUG RUSTED SO IT WAS IN OPERATIVE.  AFTER PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED THE CAR WAS STENCILLED "LEAKY TANK DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED".

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT CARL ZERWECK WAS CALLED BY CARFOREMAN K. AMOS WHO REPORTED CAR ACFX 18644 MAY BE LEAKING.  ZERWECK FOUND THE CAR IN TRACK 5 BOWL AT CENTENNIAL YARD AND INSPECTION REVEALED VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE VALVE HANDLE PACKING NUTS AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  NO INJURIES OR SERVICE DISRUPTION OCCURED DUE TO THE INCIDENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. ZERWECK TALKED WITH DON AYERS, C F INDUSTRIES DONALDSONVILLE, AND THE CAR WILL BE CHECKED AND THE PACKING REPLACED WHEN THE CAR RETURNS.

column168: ON 12/2/93, AT APPROXIMATELY 0204 HOURS, I, RANDY WILLIAMS HAZ MAT SPECIALIST OF ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH45177, INVESTIGATED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR. THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED BY NEAL VAN SAUN/SORTER. IT WAS LOCATED IN OUR HAZMAT SORT AREA AT THE SAME LOCATION. THE SHIPMENT WAS A FIBREBOARD BOX CONTAINING A PROPERLY PREPARED PAINT SHIPMENT. THE OUTER OACKAGING HAD A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL AFFIXZED AND ALL NECESSARY MARKINGS WERE ON THE FIBREBOARD BOX. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS A STEEL DRUM OF 15 LITRE CAPACITY. IT WAS LEAKING APPROXIMATELY .5 OUNCE OF PAINT DUE TO THE SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE BEING LOOSE. THER WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGING. THE STEEL DRUM WAS A DOT 37881 CONTAINER. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO ITS ORIGINAL DESTINATION. A COPY OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATION WAS RETAINED AND ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.

CHRIS STERRITT FIRST RESPONDER TO SPILL. WEARING GLOVES, GOGGLES AND APRON BROUGHT TO PSC ONE CASE. ROGER LEMIRE EXAMINED PACKAGE WEARING GLOVES, GOGGLES AND APRON. CONSULTED DENNIS WHITE ON HOW TO TAKE CARE OF PACKAGE. OPENED PACKAGE, SMELLED BAD, AROMA CALLED DENNIS WHITE BACK AND RECOMMENDED USING SCBA. ROGER LEMIRE WORE SCBA AND CHRIS WORE SCBA AND WAS BACKUP. DENNIS SUPERVISED. DMP AND HAZ MATERIAL PROCEDURE ALL CONTAMINATED BOXES USED SOLUSORB TO CONTROL ODOR. NO SHORT TERM INJURIES TO ANYONE TO THE BEST OF MY KNOWLEDGE.

AT 01:00 HOURS SORT 11 SUPERVISOR CALLED THE THE REWRAP CAGE TO INFORM US HE HAD A DAMAGED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE. I RETRIEVED THE PACKAGE, AND PROCESSED IT USING PROPER HAZ MAT PROCEDURES. DAMAGE PORTION SCRAPPED BALANCE DELIVERED. CAPS TIGHTENED AND PACKAGE CONTENTS RETURNED. IMPROPER SHIPPING PRACTICE FORM, FILLED OUT AND SENT TO SHIPPER.
CAP WAS NOT SECURED WITH TAPE. CAP WAS LOOSE. 1/3 GALLON LEAKED, WETTING BOX. WET BOX WAS PLACED IN SPILL TUB. INCORRECT SHIPPING PRACTICE SENT TO SHIPPER.
PACKAGE FOUND WET, BOTTOM OF CONTAINER PUNCTURED BY STAPLE THAT CLOSED BOX. THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED.

CHEMIST STOPPED TO EAT LUNCH AT THE BURGER KING LOCATED IN MADISON, GA. AT APPROXIMATELY 12 NOON. MATERIAL WAS DETECTED LEAKING FROM THE VEHICLE. AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK WAS USED TO PREVENT FURTHER CONTAMINATION OF THE GROUND. THE 17E/55 THAT WAS LEAKING WAS OVERPACKED INTO A DIFFERENT 85 GALLON CONTAINER. APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON MADE CONTACT WITH THE PARKING LOT AND THE REMAINDER WAS CAUGHT WITH THE OVERPACK. THE MATERIAL ON THE GROUND WAS ABSORBED WITH VERMICULITE AND CONTAINERIZED. THE SAME PROCEDURE WAS FOLLOWED FOR THE TRAILER. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS MANIFESTED SEPARATELY, SEE ATTACHED MANIFES #35126.
DRIVER WAS FILLING THE TANK FOR HOMEOWNERS AND THE VENT WAS NOT IN THE PROPER LOCATION TO FILL SAFELY.  DRIVER OVER FILLED TANK, SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.

column168: PABLOS RAMITER AND PAT GUY PROCESSED PACKAGE
WHILE DRIVER WAS BACKING UP A STEEP DRIVEWAY. FUEL OIL CAME OUT OF DOME LID GASKET. OIL RAN ON TO GROUND. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITHIN AN HOUR. NO DAMAGE TO PROPERTY.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY PRELOADER, PUT IN HAZARDOUSE TUB AND TAKEN TO HAZARDOUS DAMAGE AREA. SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED. FOUND THAT A LOOSE CAP ON GALLON JUG CAUSED LEAKAGE, WAS ABLE TO TIGHTENED, AND TAPED CLOSED. ITEMS WERE PLACED IN A NEW CARTON, FIRST BEING DOUBLE BAGGED, AND SENT TO CONSIGNEE. ORIGINAL BOX TREATED WITH SOLUSORB, TESTED WITH PH PAPER, BAGGED AND DISCARDED. ISP CARD WAS SENT TO SHIPPER.

THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED ON PD-6 AT WHICH TIME THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE REMAINING MATERIALS WERE PUT THROUGH THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE. THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED THROUGH THE DAMAGE REPORTING PROCEDURE AT WHICH TIME A RECOMMENDATION WAS MADE ON PROPER PACKING.

CHRIS RECEIVED A CALL FROM MIKE FLYNN. ABOUT A LEAKING CORROSIVE AT TWO DOOR. USING GOGGLES, APRON AND GLOVES I ARRIVED AN FOUND THE BOX SITTING ON THE GRATES. THE BOX WAS A LITTLE WET THERE WAS NO REAL SPILLAGE. I DISCOVERED IT TO BE POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE. I PLACED IN A SPILL BUCKET WITH SPEEDY DRY AND RETURNED TO PSC ROGER LEMIRE TOOK PACKAGE FROM PSC CAGE WEARING GLOVES, GOGGLES, APRON AND SLEEVES. ROGER LOOKED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL GUIDE AND READ PROCEDURE ON THE BOX SET ON UNDAMAGED PARCEL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURE CARDBOARD BOX WITH SPEEDY DRY.

PACKAGE WAS BENG HANDLED THROUGH THE INBOUND SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE OCCURED.  A METAL PACKAGE DIVERTER WAS ROUTING PACKAGES TO THEIR DESTINATION FLIGHT SORT AREA AND WHEN THE DIVERTER INITIATED IT WAS SUSPECTED THAT THIS ACTION OF THE FRICTION AND MOVEMENT OF THE OTHER PACKAGES AROUND THE BOX CAUSED PRESSURE ON THE INNER CONTAINERS RESULTING IN THE LIDS POPPING OFF OF THE METAL CANS.  THE LIDS ON THESE CANS WERE NOT SEALED BY POSTIVIE MEANS NOR WERE THERE CLOSURE RINGS ON THE CONTAINERS.  DURING THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP OF THE SUBSTANCE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CANS HAD EVIDENCE OF SOME MARKING AND LABELS THAT SUGGESTED THE MATERIAL TO BE HAZARDOUS.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND AN MSDS REQUESTED.  THE MSDS WE INTIALY RECIEVED FROM THE SHIPPER DIDN'T APPEAR TO AGRESS WITH THE SUBSTANCE WE WERE HANDLING SO THE SPILL CLEAN UP SPECIALISTS HANDLING THE SPILL CALLED THE MANUFACTURER OF THE MATERIAL AND REQUESTED AND ADDITIONAL MSDS THAT WAS MORE IN LINE WITH THE DESCRIPTION OF THE MATERIALS BEING HANDLED.  THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND THE F.A.A. WAS CONTACTED TO COME OUT AND LOOK AT THE SHIPMENT.  SPECIALS AGENTS JOHN BOCKIUS AND BOB BINDLEY RESPONDED TO THE CALL AND ARE INTITIATING AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE SHIPMENT.  AS AN ADDITIONAL NOT THIS SPILL CONTAINED 37 DEGREE OTHER PACKAGES SIX OF WHICH WERE FOOD STUFFS.

column168: ON 12/22/93 AT 0212 SORT SUPERVISOR, JIM KERTAI REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING AND EMMITTING AN ODOR.  THIS IS MARKED PAINT, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1263.  JIM KERTAI IS LOCATED AT THE AIRBORNE EXPRESS OFFICE IN SOUTH BEND, IN.  JIM WAS ADVISED THAT ABX AIR WOULD SEND HIM A SALVAGE DRUM TO FORWARD THIS SHIPMENT TO THE HAZMAT OFFICE SO ONE OF THE HAZMAT COORDINATORS COULD DO AN INVESTIGATION ON THIS SHIPMENT.  ON 12/24/93, THIS SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED BY HAZMAT COORDINATOR MICHAEL A FRYE.  HAZMAT SPECIALIST, MATT RAGER DONED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE CONTENTS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS A ONE QUART, METAL RECEPTICLE. THERE WAS A POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE.  CLOSE TO THE TOP OF THE METAL RECEPTICLE WAS AN INDENTATION.  THIS CAUSED THE CLOSURE TO FAIL, ALLOWING THE PAINT TO LEAK. THERE WAS NO VISABLE DAMAGE TO THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

ON DEC. 2, 1993 ABOUT 4:30 PM JOHN SULLIVAN (DRIVER) WAS PUMPING OFF A LOAD OF #2 FUEL INTO A ABOVE GROUND TANK (10000 GALLONS. TOWARDS THE END OF PUMPING OFF THE LOAD, THE HOSE ON DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP CAME OFF. JOHN IMMEDIATELY SHUT-DOWN THE TRANSFER. THERE WAS ABOUT 5-7 GALLONS THAT SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD, THEN ONTO THE ASPHALT.  JOHN AND A LOCAL EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP THE SPILL USING SPEEDY DRY AND SORBENT PADS. JOHN RETURNED ALL THE PADS AND SPEEDY DRY. THEY WERE TAKEN TO, AND DISPOSED OF BY OUR LOCAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR, CLEAN HARBORS IN SO. PORTLAND, ME. THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
column172: Tank trailer, semi-trailer or full trailer (two axles)

column168: ON TUESDAY, DECEMBER 27, 1993, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:45 AM, JACK MEYERS, ONE OF OUR ES DRIVERS, ARRIVED AT SHERWIN WILLIAMS IN OKLAHOMA CITY. AFTER CONVERSING WIHT THE CUSTOMER, HE RETURNED TO THE TRUCK AND NOTICED SMALL DROPS OF MATERIAL ON THE CONCRETE. THE TRUCK WAS SITUATED AT AN ANGLE THAT PROBABLY CAUSED OUR DRIVER TO SPOT THE LEAK. JACK ENTERED THE TRAILER TO DETMINE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND DISCOVERED IT WAS FROM ACONTAINER NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A 230 GALLON POLY TOTE TANK HAD A HAIRLINE CRACK ON THE TOP LEFT LIP OF THE PORTABLE TANK. AFTER IDENTIFYING THE SOURE, JACK DETERMINED THAT HE COULD NOT MOVE THE TANK IN ORDER TO REPAIR THE LEAK. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED BY JACK; CHEMTREC IN TURN NOTIFIED ASHLAND. ASHLAND THEN CALLED JACK AND A CONFERENCE CALL WAS MADE BETWEEN BILL OLASIN AND RANDY WLED. A PLAN OF ACTION WAS DECIDED. RANDY DISPACTCHED ANOTHER OKLAHOMA CITY DRIVER, JIM WHIPPLE, WHO CAME WITH A PALLT JACK AND EMPTY DRUMS TO HELP JACK. ONCE ALL THE DRUMS WERE MOVED SO THAT JACK AND JIM COULD GET TO THE TOTE, THEY DETERMINED THAT AN EPOXY PATCH COULD BE APPLIED. IT WAS ALSO DECIDED THAT THE TOTE WAS TRAVEL WORTHY AND THE PATCH WAS SUFFICIENT. THE KITTY LITTER THAT JACK APPLIED TO THE FLOOR OF VAN AS WELL AS THE GROUND WAS CAPTURED AND PLACED IN A DRUM. UPON INVESTIGATION, THE TOTE HAD BEEN INSPECTED AT THE GENERATOR'S LOCATION, BJ SERVICES IN MARSHALL, TEXAS. IT WAS TRANSPORTED FROM MARSHALL TO GARLAND AND THEN REMANIFESTED TO BE DISPOSED OF AT RINECO. PRIOR TO LOADING FOR TRANSPORT TO RINECO, THE TOTE WAS AGAIN INSPECTED AND NO CRACKS OR LEAKS WERE OBSERVED. BASED UPON OUR DISCUSSION CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT, THE WEATHER COULD HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE CRACK. IT HAD BEEN IN THE 70'S IN DALLAS PRIOR TO SHIPMENT- THE WEATHER IN OKLAHOMA CITY WAS IN THE UPPER 20'S WHEN JACK ARRIVED. THE CUSTOMER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE TOTE MANUFACTURER. IT IS MY OPINION THAT THIS INCIDENT COULD NOT HAVE BEEN PREVENTED AND I COMMEND JACK ON HIS HANDLING OF THE LEAK. I WAS NOT IN THE OFFICE THE MORNING THAT IT OCCURED- I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT ABOUT 9:30 AM AND WAS IN COMMUNICATION WITH JACK CONCERNING TH ECOURSE OF ACTION THAT WAS TAKEN. IN THE FUTURE, WE WILL USE THE IC&S FORM THAT HAS DETAILED INFORMATION REGARDING TOTE TANKS AND THEIR INTEGRITY. THIS INCIDENT HAS ALSO BEEN DISCUSSED WITH OUR OTHER DRIVER, KEVIN SADLER, TO PREVENT THIS FROM EVER HAPPENING AGAIN.

I GOT A PHONE CALL FROM PD-13 MARK, TELLING ME HE HAD A SPILL ON HIS BELT, THAT HAD A 5 PART LABEL. HE ALSO TOLD ME IT WAS IN SPILL TUB. I ASKED IF IT HAD LEAKED ANYWHERE ELSE, HE SAID NO AND I ASKED WHAT IT WAS AND HE TOLD ME IT WAS ISOPROPANOL. I WENT RIGHT AWAY TO PICK IT UP AND BRING IT BACK TO PAC. I OPEN TO FIND THE 5 GALLON CONTAINER HAD A SMALL LEAK IN IT. I CUT CARDBOARD UP THAT WAS WET AND PROCESS IT THROUGH THE DMP PROCEDURE I FINISH ABOUT 10:10.

column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: OUR DRIVER, TIMOTHY ZIEGLER, HAD ATTACHED THE NECESSARY LINES TO UNLOAD A LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. HE CLAIMS HE FOLLOWED ALL COMPANY AND CUSTOMER SAFETY PROCEDURES. THIS FACT WAS VERIFIED BY AN EMPLOYEE AT BIOKYOWA WHO WITNESSED THE HOOK UPS. AS OUR DRIVER OPENED THE BUTTERFLY VALVE AT THE TOP OF THE TRAILER TO COMMENCE UNLOADING, THE PLASTIC TUBING BELOW THE VALVE CRACKED HORIZONTALLY. THE ACID SPRAYED OUR DRIVER AND KNOCKED HIM OFF THE TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND. IT TOOK BIOKYOWA EMPLOYEES 10-15 MINUTES TO SHUT THE ACID FLOW DOWN. IN THAT TIME 2026 GALLONS OF ACID WERE LOST. NONE OF THE ACID FLOWED INTO SEWERS. THE PLANT USED SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL. SOME DIRT WILL NEED TO BE REMEDIATED. MOST OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON ASPHALT. OUR DRIVER WAS WEARING FULL PROTECTIVE GEAR. HE RECEIVED A MINOR BURN ON HIS NECK AND A BRUISED HEEL. OUR MECHNICS AND FACTORY REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE MANUFACTURER OF THE FAILED PLASTIC TUBE ALL CLAIM THEY HAVE NEVER SEEN AN EQUIPMENT FAILURE LIKE THIS ONE.
THE DRIVE HAD HOOKED UP TO TANK FILL PIPE AN A QUART OF OIL LEAKED OUT OF FITTING. THE OIL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE FITTING WAS TIGHTENED.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RECEIVED TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION FROM CESAR TREVINO, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, LAS VEGAS, NEVADA, THAT TANK CAR NATX 38284 WAS AT THE VALLEY YARD (NORTHEAST OF LAS VEGAS) AND LEAKING FROM WHAT APPEARED TO BE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  MYO TREVINO CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, REBEL OIL, AND REQUESTED ONE OF THEIR SUPERVISORS INSPECT THE CAR.  MR LARRY RATHJE, TERMINAL SUPERVISOR, REBEL OIL, INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM WAS ACTUALLY COMING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  MR RATHJE INSPECTED THE TOP PORTION AND DEVELOPED THE 3" LIQUID LINE WAS LEAKING.  THE BALL VALVE WAS CLOSED, HOWEVER, PRODUCT WAS STILL ABLE TO BYPASS THE CLOSURE.  HE ALSO NOTED THE PLUG FOR THE LIQUID LINE WAS LOOSE, AND IN TIGHTENING THE PLUG, WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK.  NOTIFICATIONS WHERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR NOTIFICATION PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORROSIVE ACTION.  NEVADA DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND ISSUED MISSION #H931230C.  ADDITIONAL AGENCIES FOR NOTIFICATION WERE CLOSED.  NO FURTHER ACTIONS WILL BE REQUIRED ON THIS INCIDENT DUE TO THE TYPE OF PRODUCT AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT SPILLED.

column168: AT 1650 HOURS REGINOAL MANAGER CTS, TOM ROBINSON RECEIVED A CALL FROM UPRR MTO NORM KIRK.  KIRK ADVISED THAT OXY CHEM AT TAFT, LA. REPORTED THAT TANK CAR GATX 92227 APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS AT THE NORTH END OF TRACK #103 AT TAFT YARD.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT IT WAS NO LONGER LEAKING, BUT HAD BEEN LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID FROM THE PACKING NUT OF THE OPERATING STEM OF THE TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  ROBINSON WAS ABLE TO SECURE THE PACKING NUT ABOUT THREE QUARTERS OF A TURN.  HE ALSO HAD TO REMOVE SEAL "TEXAS EASTMAN 16956" FROM THE STUFFING BOX COVER.  ROBINSON DISCUSSED THE SITUATION WITH KIRK AND KIRK ADVISED THAT THE CAR WOULD BE SPOTTED TO WITCO, THE CONSIGNEE, FIRST THING IN THE MORNING.  ROBINSON TELEPHONE CHEMTREC AND SUBSEQUENTLY TALKED TO MR LARRY FRANCE AND MR CHUCK DAVIS OF THE SITUATION, THE CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN AND THE PLAN TO SPOT THE CAR TO WITCO IN THE MORNING.  ROBINSON FURTHER ADVISED THAT EASTMAN CHEMICAL SHOULD CONTACT WITCO TO ADVISE OF THE PROBLEM ENCOUNTERED WITH THE CAR AND TO REPAK THE STUFFING BOX PRIOR TO RELOADING THE CAR.  DAVIS STATED THAT HE WOULD FOLLOW UP ON BOTH POINTS.

column168: BE ADVISED ON 12-14-93 - NIGHT OPS, HAZ MAT COORD. FRANCES VANCE AND PART-TIME HAZ TECHNICHIAN JIM GILLIAM WERE ADVISED OF A SPILL WITH AN ODOR ON A CUSHMAN OUTSIDE DOOR A-14 LOCATED ON THE PROPERTY OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH45177. SPILL REPORTED AT 0259; SPILL TEAM ON SCENE 0303. INVESTIGATION OF A FIBREBOARD BOX WAS LEAKING. SMALL FIBREBOARD BOX FOUND INSIDE A LARGE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS LEAKING. SMALL FIBREBOARD BOX CONTAINED ONE 1-QT METAL CONTAINER WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES LEAKING - PPG-DFXO7 SUPERCHARGER. THIS BOX ALSO CONTAINED FOUR OTHER PAINT RELATED ITEMS THAT DID NOT LEAK. THIS SHIPMENT WAS RESEALED, BAGGED, AND TAGGED AS A HOLD IN ILN HAZ MAT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD IN THE ILN HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY. CLEAR OF SCENE 0321. AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED FOR THE LEAKING SHIPMENT, UPON RECEIPT OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET, THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME FOR THIS MATERIAL IS PAINT - CLASS 3, UN1263.

PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING. EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE PLASTIC BOTTLE(S) HAD A RUPTURED SEAM THAT ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED. PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

MANIFEST WAS NOT COMPLETE SINCE THE SPILL OCCURRED ON C.S.U. PROPERTY CONTIGUOUS.   AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM ON DECEMBER 9, 1993, A RELEASE OF WASTE MERCURY OCCURRED AT COLORADO STATE UNIVERSITY.  ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES (EHS) WAS TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM THE CHEMISTRY BUILDING TO THE TRANSPORT VEHICHLE.  A BOX CONTAINING THREE BOTTLES OF MERCURY FELL OFF THE CART ONTO THE CEMENT PAVEMENT BREAKING ONE BOTTLE. THIS BOTTLE CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 1.3 LBS. OF WASTE MERCURY (ATTACHED IS THE REQUEST FOR DISPOSAL FORM).  THE SPILL OCCURRED IN THE RECEIVING AREA BETWEEN THE CHEMISTRY AND BIOCHEMISTRY AND RADIATION BIOLOGY BUILDINGS. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE CEMENT PARKING AREA. EHS BARRICADED THE AREA OF THE SPILL WITH CAUTION TAPE AND CONTACTED VIA CELLULAR PHONE FOR ADDITIONAL EHS ASSISTANCE.  THE ADDITIONAL STAFFING BROUGHT THE MERCURY VACCUM WHICH UTILIZED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  AFTER SPILL WAS CLEANED UP, EHS CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER SINCE THIS SPILL MAY HAVE EXCEEDED THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY (RQ).  THE INFORMATION WAS REPORTED TO PETTY OFFICER LLOYD AND THE REPORT NUMBER IS 211-913.  IN ADDITION, THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH, EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT UNIT AND OFFICE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT (CONTACT PERSON, KEN TELEEN) AND POUDRE FIRE AUTHORITY (RON GONZALOS).  THE FOLLOWING RECOMMEDATION WAS IMPLEMENTED TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS. BEFORE TRANSPORTING WASTE, EHS STAFF WILL ENSURE THAT ALL WASTES ARE PROPERLY PACKAGED TO PREVENT BREAKAGE IF DROPPED. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS OR CONCERNS REGARDING THIS INCIDENT, PLEASE CONTACT JIM COY AT (303) 491-4830.

A CAN OF FLEATROL FOGGER HAD A BROKEN VALVE. THE CAN'S VAPORS DISPURSED INSIDE THE PACKAGE CAR.  THIS CAUSED THE DRIVER TO HAVE CLASSIC SYMPTOMS. HE THEN PULLED OVER AND CALLED IN TO HIS MANAGER JIM HANSEN. JIM TOLK FRANK TO GET OUT OF CAR INTO THE FRESH AIR.  A SUPERVISOR TOOK FRANK AND HIS HELPER TO THE HOSPITAL.  THE PACKAGE CAR WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE CENTER.  THE CONTENTS WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING MALLINKRODT DISPOSAL METHOD. AN ISP CARD WAS WRITTEN AND SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR FOLLOW-UP WITH THEIR SHIPPER TO CORRECT FUTURE SHIPMENTS.

I RECEIVED A CALL FROM SCOTT FILLMAN AT 14:00PM. HE SAID IT WAS A 5 PART HAZARDOUS SPILL.  IT WAS ALREADY PUT IN A SPILL BUCKET AND I TOLD HIM THE PROPER PROCEDURE. WEARING GLOVES, GOGGLES, AND APRON I USED THE DECISION TREE AND BROUGHT CONTAINED SPILL TO CAGE. AFTER LOOKING IN EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE, DMP EXCEPTION BOOK AND CONSULTING WITH JEFF LABOISSURE, I PUT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURE SPILL WITH SPEEDI DRY AND WAS DONE AT 14:30. I SENT UNDAMAGED ON BECAUSE ONLY 3 TABLESPOONS SPILLED.

column168: REGIONAL MGR CHEMICAL SAFETY DEAN WHITLEY WHILE MAKING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS UNION PACIFIC HINKLE YARD, HINKLE OREGON, INSPECTED TANK CAR JRSX 1033. NOTED PRODCUT LWAKING FROM PACKING AROUND OPERATING HANDLE FOR BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. BOLTS SECURING PACKING FLANGE AROUND OPERATING HANDLE WERE TIGHTENED. THIS SLOWED VOLUME OF LEAK; HOWEVER, DID NOT COMPLETELY STOP FLOW. A PLASTIC BUCKET WAS SECURED UNDERNEATH LEAK. DUANE KING, SIMPLOT COMPANY WAS FURNISHED DETAILS. ON DECEMBER 30, 1993, CONTENTS OF TANK CAR JRSX 1033 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR GATX52845. CHEMTREC REPRESENTATIVE JOW MILAZZO WAS FURNISHED DETAILS.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY S. COVI WAS NOTIFIED BY REGIONAL MANAGER CTS D WHITELY, THAT TANK CAR GATX 16544 WAS IN POCATELLO RECEIVING YARD AND WAS LEAKING PRODUCT PROFUSELY. MCTS S. COVI RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THE RUBBER LINER HAD APPARENTLY FAILED AND DETERIORATED TANK WHICH ALLOWED LEAK OF PRODUCT. EXACT LEAK COULD NOT BE DETERMINED DUE TO THE JACKET ON THE TANK CAR. THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY DIKED AND JR SIMPLOT RESPONDED AND SODA ASH WAS BROUGHT IN TO AID IN DIKING AND NEUTRALIZING PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN GATX 16544 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR GATX 26090 TO REDUCE LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT. AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED BY REMOVAL OF RAIL AND NEUTRALIZING AND REMOVAL OF SOIL. LEACHING WAS ALSO USED IN SOME TRACK AREAS BY DIGGING TRENCHES ALONG THE RAIL AND LEACHING A LIME WATER SOLUTION THROUGH THE RAIL/SOIL. TRENCHES WERE LINED WITH PLASTIC AND CRUSHED LIMESTONE. RESIDUE WAS THEN VACUUMED INTO TRUCK AND TRANSPORTED TO JR SIMPLOT FOR PROPER TREATMENT/DISPOSAL.
THIS PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PLACED IN A DMP BAG IN THE HAZ MAT STORAGE AREA.

ON DECEMBER 20, 1993, THE NPHOT 18 DERAILED AT SAN HILL, TX. 18 CARS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT, 4 OF WHICH WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESIDUE TANK CARS.  TANK CAR DOWX 3701, 23RD FROM THE HEAD END, WAS MOVING UNDER UP WB 12 14 979797, SALT LAKE CITY, UT TO FREEPORT, TX., AS A RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED 1,1,1, TRICHLOROETHANE, 6.1 UN2831, PG 111.    INITIAL DAMAGE ASSESSMENT SHOWED THE CAR FLATTENED IN THE MIDDLE. ONCE THE CAR WAS MOVED, IT BECAME APPARENT THAT THERE WAS A LARGE TEAR, 4'-6' LONG, IN ITS SIDE.  THE CAR WAS ROLLED AWAY FROM THE TEAR WHEN MOVED, TO AVOID POSSIBLE SPILLAGE.  BECAUSE OF POSSIBLE RESIDUE, THE TEAR WAS COVERED WITH PLASTIC SHEETING FOR PROTECTION.  TANK CAR ACFX 86049, 27TH FROM THE HEAD END, WAS MOVING UNDER UP WB 12 14 979797, SALT LAKE CITY, UT TO HOUSTON, TX., AS A RESIDUE:  LAST CONTAINED TOLUENE, 3, UN11294, PG 11. THERE WAS A LARGE DENT MIDWAY ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR, BUT THE TOP FITTINGS WERE INTACT. THE TANK SHELL WAS ALSO INTACT. TANK CAR UTLX 201062, 34TH FROM THE HEAD END, WAS MOVING UNDER UP WB 12 08 979797, BARNES, OREGON TO BAYTOWN, TX., AS A RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED TOLUENE, 3, UN1294, PG 11. THERE WAS A LARGE DENT ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR. FITTINGS AND SHELL WERE INTACT. TANK CAR GATX 39902, 35TH FROM THE HEAD END, WAS MOVING UNDER UP WB 12 17979797, BARNES OREGON TO HOUSTON, TX., AS A RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED METHYL ETHYL KETONE, 3, UN1193, PG 11. THERE WERE MINOR SCRAPS AND DENTS, BUT THE 2 COMPARTMENT CAR WAS INTACT. ALL THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TANK CARS INVOLVED WERE MOVED TO CLEAR THE MAINLINE BY 0800 HRS., 12-21-93. DOW REPRESENTATIVE VERGEL PERRY AND UPRR CTS REGIONAL MANAGER TOM ROBINSON WERE ENROUTE TO INSPECT THE DAMAGE SUSTAINED TO DOWX 3701 AND DETERMINE PROPER DISPOSITION.

ON 12/09/93 AT APPROXIMATELY 0206 HRS, I, KAREN NICHOLS HAZ MAT COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC, 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 451777 WAS NOTIFIED OF A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR. IT WAS REPORTED BY MICHAEL AEH/SORT SUPERVISOR OF THE SAME LOCATION, AND REMOVED FROM THE AREA BY JIM GILLIAM/HAZ MAT SPECIALIST. THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX. THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS OF THE BOX. THERE WERE NO SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARDS BOX I FOUND 1 X 32 OUNCE SIZE GLASS BOTTLE WITH A METAL SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE. THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE. THIS GLASS BOTTLE WAS ONLY HALF FULL AND IT DID NOT APPEAR TO HAVE LEAKED. THIS GLASS BOTTLE WAS WRAPPED IN BUBBLE PACKING. ALSO INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WERE TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH POINTED-TIP TOP FITTING. THESE TOP FITTINGS HAD HOLES IN THE TIPS THAT WERE NOT CLOSED UP BY ANY MEANS. THERE WAS RESIDUE OF THE SAME PRODUCT IN EACH ONE OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES THAT SEEMED TO HAVE LEAKED OUT AND DAMPENED THE OUTER FIBREBOARD. ALL OF THESE INNER RECEPTACLES CONTAINED THE SAME LIQUID. ALSO INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS 1 GLASS RECEPTACLE CONTAINING ACRYLIC POWDER. TIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

THIS ODOR WAS LOCATED IN SORT BLDG B, 2ND FLOOR, ON THE PROPERTY OF AIRBORNE EXPRESS, INC. 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH. 45177. CFR 06 RESPONDED AT 0242 AND ON SCENE AT 0245. THIS ODOR WAS CALLED IN BY JOHN CONNER, ILN SORTER. ON SCENE CERT 13 (RANDY WILLIAMS) ILN PART-TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN AND CERT 13 (JEFFREY HOSTETLER) ILN HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, DONNED CARTRIDGE MASKS AND INVESTIGATED SHIPMENT. THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL 2-1 GALLON METAL CONTAINERS OF PAINT THINNER. THESE WERE LAYING ON THEIR SIDES IN THE FIBREBOARD BOX, AND ONE OF WHICH HAD LEAKED. BOTH STATED THAT THEY WERE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1263. THIS SHIPMENT WAS RETAPED, BAGGED, REMOVED FROM THE AREA, AND TAKEN TO ILN HAZ BASE FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. CLEAR SCENE AT 0253.

ON DECEMBER 30, 1993 AT APPROXIMATELY 1755 HRS, OUR DRIVER WAS FILLING MR. WALTER SCHMUNKS FUEL TANK. IN THE PROCESS OF FILLING THE TANK A SEAM RUPTURED, CAUSING FUEL TO BE SPILLED ON THE FLOOR. WE DO NOT OWN THE TANK, IT IS OWNED BY THE CUSTOMER. OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWED PROPER PROCEDURE BY NOTIFYING THE FIRE DEPT, EPA AND THE OWNER OF PETRO MART. HE ALSO PUT SORB-IT ON THE GROUND TO START ABSORBING THE OIL. HE ALSO CALLED THE CLEAN UP COMPANY SAMSEL, TO FINISH THE J0B.

column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED THROUGH THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED.  IT APEARED THAT THE CLOSURE OF THE INNER CONTAINER WAS NOT SEALED OR SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE BULK OF THE SPILL OCCURRED ON THE INSIDE OF THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABLES, OR SHIPPING PAPERS ON EITHER THE INNER CONTAINERS OR THE OUTER BOX.  AN MSDS SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER VERIFYING THAT THE COMMODITY DOES EXHIBIT CORROSIVE PROPERITIES THAT CAUSE THE COMMODITY TO BE REGULATED. THE SHIPPERS HAS BEEN NOT IDENTIFIED AND THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE F.A.A.

12-29-93 OPS 0103-PT HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN, MARK GRIFFITH, REPORTED A SPILL IN THE HAZ MAT SORT OF OUR FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER., WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HAZ MAT SPILL TEAM CONSISTING OF HAZ MAT COORDINATIOR FRAN VANCE AND PT HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN, MARK GRIFFITH, WERE ON SCENE AT THE TIME SPILL WAS REPORTED.  WE FOUND A GRAY STEEL DRUM ON THE FEED BELT LEAKING A WHITE/GRAY THICK LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE BELT, PLACED INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS, AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR SHIPMENT ONTO DESTINATION.  THE FEED BELT WAS CLEANED OF ALL THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK APPEARS TO BE FROM THE STEEL DRUM FREEZING AND THE BOTTOM SEAM OF THE DURM BURSTING IN THE SUB ZERO TEMPERATURE.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0332.  MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED TO THE DRUM WERE AS FOLLOWS: 1,1,1, TRICHLOROETHANE, 6.1, UN2831, PKG GP 111, KEEP AWAY FROM FOOD STUFF HAZARD LABEL.  MANFACTURES WARNING LABEL FOR USE OF THE PRODUCT ADHESIVE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: HAZ SORT SUPERVISOR, TOM ARCHIBALD, REPORTED A SPILL IN THE HAZ SORT AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AS A LIQUID, CLASS 3, NO ODORS, 3 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT. THOSE EMPLOYEES ARE: SUSAN STOTLER, PATTY STEELE, AND TOM ARCHIBALD. HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, FRAN VANCE, AND PART-TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIAN, MARK GRIFFITH, WERE ON SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WET. WE OPENED THE BOX, FOUND THE CONTENTS TO BE ETHYL ALCOHOL, CLASS 3, UN1170, PACKAGED IN 8 16 OUNCE GLASS CONTAINERS WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. ALL OF THESE GLASS CONTAINERS WERE PACKAGED ON THEIR SIDES AGAINST OUTER PACKAGE ORIENTATION. THERE WAS A CARDBOARD DIVIDER IN THE MIDDLE OF THE BOX WITH 4 OF THE GLASS CONTAINERS OF EACH SIDE OF THE DIVIDER. ONE OF THE GLASS CONTAINERS WAS BROKEN DUE TO INADEQUATE CUSHIONING BETWEEN THE GLASS CONTAINERS. THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS THAT WAS ATTACHED TO THE PACKAGE INDICATED THE CONTENTS TO BE ETHYL ALCOHOL, UN 1170, FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL, UN-4G 4GV/14.2/S/93, USA & AA0676, APPROVED FOR AIR SHIPMENTS, AND THE DOTE-8249 MARKING. ALSO ATTACHED TO THE BOX WAS THE DOT-E-8249 EXEMPTION. INCLUDED ON THE TOP OF THE BOX WAS THE AIR WAYBILL AND THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS ETHYL ALCOHOL, UN1170, 2 LITERS, CLASS 3, PG II, AND THIS END UP. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT PACKAGED ACCORDING TO THE DOT-E-8249 EXEMPTION. THERE IS NO INDICATION IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS THAT ETHYL ALCOHOL NEEDS A POISON LABEL TO WARRANT THIS EXEMPTION. NEVERTHELESS, THE EXEMPTION WAS ATTACHED TO THE PACKAGE. THE SHIPMENT WAS RESEALED, PLACED INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS, AND REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR TRANSPORTATION ON TO THE SHIPMENT DESTINATION. CLEAR OF SCENE 0327. A COPY OF THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GODDS AND A COPY OF DOT-E-8249 EXEMPTION WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.
NO REMARKS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 P.M. ON 12/21/93, I WAS NOTIFIED BY JEFF LIEPELT, MANAGER OF SERVICE, THAT TANK CAR UTLX 49620 HAD DEVELOPED A LEAK WHILE BEING HANDLED IN ICRR'S GLENN YARD.  UPON ARRIVAL I FOUND THAT THE TANK HAD FAILED IN THE AREA WHERE THE STUB STILL CONNECTS TO THE TANK HEAD. THE METAL WAS TORN AT THE CONNECTION PAD. THE AAR, CAR OWNER AND FRA WERE NOTIFIED OF THE FAILURE.
